The diseases of globalization
Globalization is put to a severe test as never before.
Tensions are simmering everywhere.
The vast majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with an economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are stuck in slow growth and risk a new recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For open market and free trade advocates, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its advantages apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Certain regions of the world have gained considerable benefits from globalization, particularly East Asia and China over the past few years.
Certain regions, however, have gained meager benefits, particularly sub-Saharan Africa.
The US government claims that poor countries are responsible for most of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, asserted by American leaders, is caused by the inaptitude of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let's consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the last in international comparisons of government (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
The countries with a high population and therefore the large internal markets tend to grow more rapidly than the countries with a low population.
(Like all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
The coastal countries tend to be more performing than the landlocked countries.
The countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than the countries with lower levels of malaria.
The developing countries that are close to rich markets, like Mexico, tend to be more performing than the countries that are far from the main markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If the rich countries do not care much about these structural problems, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If rich countries reject responsibility on the unfortunate countries by claiming that they are in some way culturally or politically unfit to benefit from globalisation, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify unrest.
This in turn will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than that offered by the rich countries, and particularly America.
This approach must start with the most urgent task, namely addressing the basic needs of the poorest people in the world.
In some cases, their sufferings can be alleviated mainly thanks to better governance within their country.
But in others, an honest look at the evidence gathered will reveal that the main causes of poverty involve diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distance from markets, etc.
A honest evaluation would indicate further that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds to solve such problems on their own.
Instead of seeing rich countries giving more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require rich countries to provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
An instance will illustrate this situation strikingly.
Health control requires a health system capable of providing survival medicines and basic preventive services like bed nets to fight malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about 40 dollars per person per year.
This amount represents only a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than 2,000 dollars per person and per year on health, but it exceeds the reach of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of 200 dollars per person.
A functioning health system would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Although Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers due to diseases as long as it does not receive adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires us to think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of reproaching the poor for their "sins", we must offer careful diagnoses, like a good doctor, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that delay their economic growth and development.
In certain regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem is mainly caused by geographical isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air connections, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions create productive links with the world.
The rich countries must contribute to the financing of these projects.
In Black Africa, the main challenges are related to the control of diseases, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, more foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems are related to the lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific problems.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent in globalization seriously.
The one-size-fits-all ideology of the Washington Consensus is outdated.
Before the war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of making globalization benefit everyone.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the rich and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
